#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:19
msgid ""
"In general everyday usage, Cryptography is the act or art of writing in "
"secret characters. In technical jargon it may be defined as the science of "
"using mathematics to encrypt and decrypt data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:20
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptanalysis"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:23
msgid ""
"Cryptanalysis is the study of how to compromise (defeat) cryptographic "
"mechanisms. It is the science of cracking code, decoding secrets, violating "
"authentication schemes, and in general, breaking cryptographic protocols."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:24
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptology"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:27
msgid ""
"Cryptology is the discipline of cryptography and cryptanalysis combined. "
"Cryptology is the branch of mathematics that studies the mathematical "
"foundations of cryptographic methods."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "Encryption"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:31
msgid ""
"Encryption is the transformation of data into a form that is as close to "
"impossible as possible to read without the appropriate knowledge (e.g. a "
"key). Its purpose is to ensure privacy by keeping information hidden from "
"anyone for whom it is not intended."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:32
#, no-wrap
msgid "Decryption"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:35
msgid ""
"Decryption is the reverse of encryption; it is the transformation of "
"encrypted data back into an intelligible form."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:36
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cipher"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:39
msgid "A method of encryption and decryption is called a cipher."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:41
msgid "Hash Functions (Digest algorithms)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:43
msgid ""
"Cryptographic hash functions are used in various contexts, for example to "
"compute the message digest when making a digital signature. A hash function "
"compresses the bits of a message to a fixed-size hash value in a way that "
"distributes the possible messages evenly among the possible hash values. A "
"cryptographic hash function does this in a way that makes it extremely "
"difficult to come up with a message that would hash to a particular hash "
"value. Some examples of the best known and most widely used hash functions "
"are described below."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "**a)** - **SHA-1 (Secure Hash Algorithm)** -This is a cryptographic hash algorithm published by the United States Government. It produces a 160 bit hash value from an arbitrary length string. It is considered to be very good.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "**b)**- **MD5 (Message Digest Algorithm 5)** - is a cryptographic hash algorithm developed at RSA Laboratories. It can be used to hash an arbitrary length byte string into a 128 bit value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "Algorithm"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:51
msgid ""
"It describes a step-by-step problem-solving procedure, especially an "
"established, recursive computational procedure for solving a problem in a "
"finite number of steps. Technically, an algorithm must reach a result after "
"a finite number of steps. The efficiency of an algorithm can be measured as "
"the number of elementary steps it takes to solve the problem. There are two "
"classes of key-based algorithms. They are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "**a) **-- **Symmetric Encryption Algorithms ( secret-key)**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:55
msgid ""
"Symmetric algorithms use the same key for encryption and decryption (or the "
"decryption key is easily derived from the encryption key). Secret key "
"algorithms use the same key for both encryption and decryption (or one is "
"easily derivable from the other). This is the more straightforward approach "
"to data encryption, it is mathematically less complicated than public-key "
"cryptography. Symmetric algorithms can be divided into stream ciphers and "
"block ciphers. Stream ciphers can encrypt a single bit of plaintext at a "
"time, whereas block ciphers take a number of bits (typically 64 bits in "
"modern ciphers), and encrypt them as a single unit. Symmetric algorithms are "
"much faster to execute on a computer than asymmetric ones."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:57
msgid ""
"Examples of symmetric algorithms are: AES, 3DES, Blowfish, CAST5, IDEA and "
"Twofish."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:59
#, no-wrap
msgid "**b) -- Asymmetric algorithms (Public-key algorithms)**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:61
msgid ""
"Asymmetric algorithms on the other hand use a different key for encryption "
"and decryption, and the decryption key cannot be derived from the encryption "
"key. Asymmetric ciphers permit the encryption key to be public, allowing "
"anyone to encrypt with the key, whereas only the proper recipient (who knows "
"the decryption key) can decrypt the message. The encryption key is also "
"called the public key and the decryption key the private key or secret key."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:63
msgid "RSA is probably the best known asymmetric encryption algorithm."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "Digital Signature"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:67
msgid ""
"A digital signature binds a document to the owner of a particular key. "
"Digital signatures are used to verify that a message really comes from the "
"claimed sender."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:69
msgid ""
"The digital signature of a document is a piece of information based on both "
"the document and the signer's private key. It is typically created through "
"the use of a hash function and a private signing function (encrypting with "
"the signer's private key). A digital signature is a small amount of data "
"that was created using some secret key, and there is a public key that can "
"be used to verify that the signature was really generated using the "
"corresponding private key."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:71
msgid ""
"Several methods for making and verifying digital signatures are freely "
"available but the most widely known algorithm is the RSA public-key "
"algorithm."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptographic Protocols"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:75
msgid ""
"Cryptography works on many levels. On one level you have algorithms, such as "
"block ciphers and public key cryptosystems. Building upon these you obtain "
"protocols, and building upon protocols you find applications (or other "
"protocols). Below is a list of common everyday applications that make use of "
"cryptographic protocols. These protocols are built on lower level "
"cryptographic algorithms."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:77
msgid "i.) Domain Name Server Security (DNSSEC)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:79
msgid ""
"This is a protocol for secure distributed name services. It is currently "
"available as an Internet Draft."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:81
msgid "ii.) Secure Socket Layer (SSL)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:83
msgid ""
"SSL is one of the two protocols used for secure WWW connections (the other "
"is SHTTP). WWW security has become important as, increasing amounts of "
"sensitive information, such as credit card numbers, are being transmitted "
"over the Internet."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:85
msgid "iii.) Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol (SHTTP)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:87
msgid ""
"This is another protocol for providing more security for WWW transactions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:89
msgid "iv) E-Mail security and related services"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "**GnuPG** - The GNU Privacy Guard - is compliant with the proposed OpenPGP Internet standard as described in RFC2440.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:93
msgid "v) SSH2 Protocol"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:95
msgid ""
"This protocol is versatile for the needs of the internet, and is currently "
"used in the SSH2 software. The protocol is used to secure terminal sessions "
"and TCP connections."
msgstr ""

